{{Infobox award | name = Wildlife Photographer of the Year | current_awards = | image = Wildlife Photographer of the Year logo.svg | imagesize = | caption = | description = [[Wildlife photography]] | presenter = [[Natural History Museum, London|The Natural History Museum]] | country = United Kingdom | location = | year = 1964 | year2 = | holder = {{flagicon|SA}} Brent Stirton | website = http://www.nhm.ac.uk/wildphoto }} '''Wildlife Photographer of the Year''' is the largest wildlife photography competition in the world. It is an annual international [[wildlife photography]] competition owned by the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]. It was known as '''[[BG Group|BG]] Wildlife Photographer of the Year''' from 1990 to 2003, and briefly as '''[[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] Wildlife Photographer of the Year''', '''[[Eastman Kodak|Kodak]] Wildlife Photographer of the Year''' and '''[[Prudential plc|Prudential]] Wildlife Photographer of the Year'''. The first competition was held in 1964, with three categories and around 600 entries.<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/visit-us/whats-on/temporary-exhibitions/wpy/competition/about/history.jsp|title=Wildlife Photographer of the Year - Competition|year=2009|publisher=Natural History Museum|accessdate=2009-04-02}}</ref> In 2008 the competition received over 32,000 entries from 3100 photographers in 82 countries.<ref name=History/> There is an exhibition of the winning and commended images each year at the Natural History Museum, which later tours around the world. It is often cited as being one of the most prestigious photography competitions in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/4355628.stm|title=Peregrine swoops to photo prize|last=Amos|first=Jonathan|date=19 October 2005|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/sep/17/arts.artsnews|title=Wildlife photographers feted for animal pageantry|last=Chrisafis|first=Angelique|date=17 September 2002|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref>
A book of winning entries and runners-up has been published each year since 1992,<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Fountain Press | isbn = 0-86343-395-2 | last = Wilkinson | first = Peter |author2=Helen Gilks | title = Wildlife photographer of the year portfolio one | location = Surbiton, Surrey : | year = 1992 }}</ref> with two books being published in 1994 (the first three volumes were published the year after the corresponding competitions were held). Early volumes have become quite collectable. These portfolios are the sources of the ranking.
==Competition==
A maximum of 25 images ranging from intimate animal portraits to atmospheric landscapes, ground-breaking photojournalism to innovative technique can be submitted once a year, in 12-17 permanent and alternate categories. Since 2003 the grand prize has been selected from among the winning images of the categories and has been awarded to a single image in adult and young competition too. The photographer aged 17 and under submitting the best image receives the title “The Young Wildlife Photographer of the Year”, while the author of the best image over 17 years of age becomes “The Wildlife Photographer of the Year”. (This award has never been won in adult category more than once.) The deadline of submission of the images is around late February, and the results become public in mid-October.
The winning images are selected from among approximately 50,000 entries received from almost 100 countries around the globe, in three rounds by a prestigious and professional jury. The awards ceremony takes place in the Natural History Museum in London. On this date the latest Wildlife Photographer of the Year portfolio, introducing the winning images, comes out. Following the awards ceremony, the extremely high-quality and major Wildlife Photographer of the Year exhibition opens its gates in London and after that touring worldwide throughout the year, attracting more than 5 million visitors.
==Categories==
Photographers can enter their images into a range of categories, whose criteria are mostly based on the subject matter of the images. There are also 3 categories for under 18's, and 3 special awards. The number and name of categories changes nearly every year. In each category a winning, runner-up and several highly commended images are usually chosen, although sometimes the judges will not choose a winner or runner up in a particular category if they deem the standard of entries not to be high enough. The categories in the 2016 competition were as follows: *1. Mammals *2. Birds *3. Reptiles, Amphibians and Fishes *4. Invertebrates *5. Plants and Fungi *6. Underwater 0524+1524
*9. Urban *10. Detail *11. Impressions *12. Black and White *13. Wildlife Photojournalist: Single Image *14. Wildlife Photojournalist: Photo Story Award *15. Rising Star Portfolio Award (ages 18 to 25) *16. Wildlife Photographer Portfolio Award (ages 26 and over)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/visit/wpy/competition/adult-competition/categories.html|title=Categories {{!}} Wildlife Photographer of the Year|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>
